**Neuroimaging & Multimodal Datasets**
Alzheimer’s Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI)
Focus: MRI, PET, CSF biomarkers, genetics, and cognitive tests for Alzheimer's disease.
Access: adni.loni.usc.edu

OASIS (Open Access Series of Imaging Studies)
Focus: MRI datasets for healthy aging, Alzheimer's disease, and cognitive decline.
Access: www.oasis-brains.org

Parkinson's Progression Markers Initiative (PPMI)
Focus: Longitudinal multimodal data for Parkinson’s disease.
Access: www.ppmi-info.org

UK Biobank
Focus: Population-scale genetics, neuroimaging, and biomarker data.
Access: www.ukbiobank.ac.uk

HCP (Human Connectome Project)
Focus: Advanced neuroimaging of brain connectivity.
Access: www.humanconnectome.org

LONI Image Data Archive (IDA)
Focus: Large-scale neuroimaging data collections.
Access: ida.loni.usc.edu

**Genetics & Multi-Omics Databases**
AMP-AD Knowledge Portal (Accelerating Medicines Partnership for Alzheimer’s Disease)
Focus: Multi-omic data for AD from multiple cohorts.
Access: www.synapse.org/ampad

**GAAIN**
The Global Alzheimer’s Association Interactive Network (GAAIN) unites a diverse and geographically distributed network of data partners within a federated data platform designed to foster cohort discovery, collaboration and sharing. GAAIN represents the first open access, federated Alzheimer’s disease data discovery platform of its kind
Alzheimer's Disease Variant Portal
Focus: comprehensive resource that curates genetic association findings related to AD from over 200 genome-wide association studies (GWAS). It encompasses data from more than 80 cohorts across eight populations, offering insights into over 900 loci and 1,800 genetic variants associated with AD. 
Access: https://advp.niagads.org/

https://www.gaain.org/

ADRCSC (Alzheimer’s Disease Research Center Single-Cell Database)
Focus: ADRCSC provides single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-Seq) data from blood samples of individuals with Alzheimer’s disease (AD), Parkinson’s disease (PD), mild cognitive impairment (MCI), and healthy controls (HC). The database enables the analysis of gene expression differences across cell types, sexes, and disease states, offering insights into immune system alterations and potential biomarkers for neurodegenerative disorders.
Access: ADRCSC Database
Tools: Interactive visualizations for gene expression across different cell types and conditions.

Neurodegenerative Disease Knowledge Portal (NDKP)
Focus: The NDKP allows you to download various datasets, including phenotypes, credible sets, and epigenomic datasets. 
Access: https://ndkp.hugeamp.org/

GWAS Catalog (Genome-Wide Association Studies)
Focus: Genetic variants associated with neurodegenerative diseases.
Access: www.ebi.ac.uk/gwas

GENFI (Genetic Frontotemporal Dementia Initiative)
Focus: Longitudinal data on genetic forms of FTD.
Access: www.genfi.org

Alzheimer’s Disease Genetics Consortium (ADGC)
Focus: Large-scale AD genetic association studies.
Access: www.adgenetics.org

Prion Disease Database (PrD-DB)
Focus: Genetic and molecular studies on prion diseases.
Access: www.priondb.org

**NIAGADS**
NIAGADS is the National Institute on Aging (NIA) designated national data repository for human genetics research on Alzheimer’s Disease and related dementia (ADRD). NIAGADS maintains a high-quality data collection for ADRD genetic/genomic research and supports genetics data production and analysis. NIAGADS hosts whole genome and exome sequence data from the Alzheimer’s Disease Sequencing Project (ADSP) and other genotype/phenotype data, encompassing 209,000 samples. NIAGADS shares these data with hundreds of research groups around the world via the Data Sharing Service, a FISMA moderate compliant cloud-based platform that fully supports the NIH Genome Data Sharing Policy. NIAGADS Open Access consists of multiple knowledge bases with genome-wide association summary statistics and rich annotations on the biological significance of genetic variants and genes across the human genome. NIAGADS stands as a keystone in promoting collaborations to advance the understanding and treatment of Alzheimer’s disease.

